## Expert Summary

The square cushion cut diamond is the original cushion shape — the version buyers imagine when they search "cushion cut diamond" — and it remains the correct choice for buyers who want the pillow aesthetic in its purest, most compact form. Its relationship to the princess cut is one of the most consistently misunderstood comparisons in engagement ring shopping: same face-up footprint at equivalent carat, completely different optical character, and a price relationship that favors the cushion at G quality and the princess at D quality — The Pillow Premium running in two directions depending on the tier where the buyer is shopping.

The buying sequence that avoids the most common square cushion mistakes: filter L/W ratio to 1.00–1.05 before looking at any other specification; choose GIA for natural stones and IGI for lab grown; confirm cushion modified brilliant sub-type ("Modified" in the listing name); and if comparing to princess cut, view both shapes in person before committing — The Square Illusion cannot be resolved on paper or from photographs. Natural square cushion at G-VS quality starts at [$1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), where it undercuts comparable princess pricing; lab grown 1.5ct square cushion starts at [$1,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), where it delivers D-VVS quality in a 1.5ct cushion below the cost of any natural 1ct cushion.

The one common mistake unique to square cushion buyers is shopping without the L/W ratio filter active. Blue Nile's cushion search defaults to showing all cushion shapes mixed together; the L/W filter is critical and must be applied actively. A buyer who selects "Cushion" and sorts by price without filtering L/W ratio receives results ranging from 1.00 to 1.35 — the top of that range looks nothing like the bottom, and a 1.20 L/W stone labeled "cushion cut" is not a square cushion by any reasonable definition.

> "Square cushion cut diamonds are what I recommend for buyers who want a diamond that looks deliberately chosen — not just large, not just brilliant, but shaped with intention. The pillow outline with soft corners has a warmth and purposefulness that the princess cut's geometric precision does not have at the G quality level. At G-VS, the square cushion gives more character per dollar than any other square-shaped diamond; it is the one quality tier where the pillow look costs less than the sharp-corner alternative, and buyers who discover that often feel like they found the shape they were always meant to buy."
> — Farzana, Diamond Consultant

## Final Verdict: Which Square Cushion Cut Diamond Should You Buy?

**Best for natural at entry budget:** [GIA 1.00ct G-VS1 Cushion Modified at $1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Petite Solitaire 14K White Gold at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$2,891 total**. GIA-certified, priced below a comparable GIA princess cut at G-VS2, with the soft-corner pillow aesthetic that makes the square cushion the superior-looking choice for most buyers at this budget tier. The Pillow Premium works in the buyer's favor at this quality level.

**Best for maximum lab quality at mid-budget:** [IGI 2ct D-VVS1 Lab Cushion at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Classic Four Prong Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$3,786 total**. D color, VVS1 clarity, 2ct of square cushion modified brilliant in platinum — at a price below a natural 1ct G-VS1 plus setting combination. No visual difference under normal conditions versus a natural 2ct D-VVS1 cushion that would cost $18,000–$22,000+.

**Best for princess-versus-cushion comparison buyers:** Order both the [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Cushion at $1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the [GIA 1ct G-VS2 Princess at $2,212](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961307?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) with return policies, view them both on your hand, and return whichever one you do not choose. The Square Illusion cannot be resolved by reading about the two shapes — this is the one buying decision in the cushion category that requires in-person comparison, and Blue Nile's return policy makes the comparison essentially free.

**Best for heirloom buyers:** [GIA 1ct F-VS1 Cushion Modified at $2,064](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25944037?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Riviera Pavé 14K White Gold at $1,515](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/riviera-pave-engagement-ring-item-195326?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$3,579 total**. For buyers who want GIA natural certification and hold the ring as a long-term asset, F-VS1 in a pavé band delivers the square cushion's best face-up appearance at a price that leaves room for a matching wedding band. Natural cushion resale value holds at 30–50% of purchase price — the ring has genuine heirloom-grade value at this specification.

## FAQs: Square Cushion Cut Diamond

### What is a square cushion cut diamond?
A square cushion cut diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond with a length-to-width ratio between 1.00 and 1.05 — producing a face-up outline that reads as square with soft, rounded corners on all four sides. It is the original, classic cushion cut shape, distinct from the elongated cushion (L/W 1.15+) and the princess cut (which has sharp 90° corners). The cushion modified brilliant sub-type produces a distributed "crushed ice" sparkle across all four quadrants of the face-up area.

### What is the square cushion cut diamond price?
A GIA 1ct G-VS1 natural square cushion costs [$1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at Blue Nile. A GIA 2ct F-VVS2 costs [$13,679](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29359194?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). A GIA 3ct G-VVS2 costs [$32,692](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961123?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab grown square cushion starts at approximately [$680](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for 1ct IGI and [$1,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for IGI 1.5ct E-VVS2.

### What L/W ratio is a square cushion cut diamond?
L/W ratio 1.00–1.05 defines the square cushion outline. The optimal ratio is 1.02–1.04: visually square to any observer, with a slight lengthwise preference that prevents the stone from appearing compressed. At L/W 1.06 and above, the cushion enters the no-man's-land between square and elongated and may not appear square when set — always confirm the exact L/W ratio from the stone's listing page before purchasing.

### What is the difference between square cushion cut and princess cut?
The Square Illusion: both produce nearly identical face-up footprints at the same carat weight (princess ~5.45mm × 5.45mm versus cushion ~5.20mm × 5.20mm at 1ct), but optical character is completely different. Princess has sharp 90° corners and a geometric linear sparkle pattern; square cushion has soft rounded corners and a distributed "crushed ice" sparkle. At G-VS quality, cushion is 10–15% cheaper than princess; at D-VVS quality, cushion commands a 40–80%+ premium (The Pillow Premium).

### What is the square cushion cut vs elongated cushion cut difference?
L/W ratio and finger effect. Square cushion (L/W 1.00–1.05) sits centered and compact with equal visual weight in all directions. Elongated cushion (L/W 1.15–1.25) runs diagonally and creates a finger-lengthening effect with 8–12% more apparent face-up length. Both use the cushion modified brilliant facet structure, produce the same crushed ice sparkle, and are priced similarly at equivalent quality — the choice is purely visual preference.

### What is the square cushion cut lab grown diamond price?
IGI 1ct lab cushion starts at approximately [$680](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). IGI 1.5ct E-VVS2 costs [$1,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). IGI 2ct D-VVS1 costs [$2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). IGI 3ct D-VVS1 costs [$6,215](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25630512?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab grown delivers the same square cushion optical character as natural at 70–90% lower price — use IGI for lab, GIA for natural.

### What is the best setting for a square cushion cut diamond ring?
Four-prong solitaire at the corners is the most popular and effective setting for square cushion cut diamonds. It exposes maximum face-up area, aligns prongs symmetrically with the cushion geometry, and allows the soft corners to be visible from all angles. The [Petite Solitaire 14K White Gold at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (1,020 reviews) is the most consistently proportioned setting for square cushion stones at Blue Nile.

### What is the square cushion cut halo ring?
A square cushion cut halo ring surrounds the cushion center stone with a ring of smaller diamonds that traces the pillow outline, visually increasing the center stone's apparent size by 15–20% and creating a unified cushion-shaped impression. A 1ct square cushion in a well-proportioned cushion halo reads as a 1.3–1.5ct equivalent face-up. For halo design options and complete price builds, see [Halo Cushion Cut Diamond Ring](/halo-cushion-cut-diamond-ring); halo settings at Blue Nile start from [$1,780](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?style=halo&ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

### Does square cushion or princess cut look larger?
Princess cut looks slightly larger face-up at equivalent carat weights because its sharp corners extend to the full measured diameter — approximately 5.45mm × 5.45mm at 1ct versus 5.20mm × 5.20mm for the square cushion. However, the cushion's distributed "crushed ice" sparkle pattern creates a visual luminosity that reads as larger in motion and in normal room lighting, while the princess's geometric pattern creates a more defined but visually static impression at rest.

### What is The Square Illusion for cushion diamonds?
The Square Illusion is the consistent buyer surprise when comparing square cushion and princess side-by-side: nearly identical face-up footprints at the same carat weight, but completely different optical character — corner geometry, sparkle pattern, visual style, and ring aesthetic. Buyers who choose between these shapes based on description alone rather than in-person comparison frequently discover the wrong choice only after setting. In-person comparison (or purchase with a return policy) is the only reliable resolution.

### What is The Pillow Premium for square cushion diamonds?
The Pillow Premium is the quality-grade-dependent price gap between square cushion and princess cut diamonds at equivalent weights. At G-VS quality, cushion undercuts princess by 10–15% — a value advantage for the cushion buyer at the most popular shopping tier. At D-VVS quality, cushion commands a 40–80%+ premium over princess, driven by lower cutting yield from the cushion's rounded corners wasting D-grade rough. Buyers at G-VS get the Pillow Premium discount; buyers at D-VVS pay the Pillow Premium surcharge.

### Is square cushion the same as old mine cut diamond?
No — the square cushion is the modern evolution of the Old Mine Cut, not the cut itself. [Antique cushion cut diamonds](/antique-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) (Old Mine Cuts) have a smaller table, higher crown, visible culet face-up, and were cut without modern measurement tools. The square cushion retains the soft-corner pillow shape but uses contemporary facet proportions, GIA certification standards, and machine-assisted cutting precision that Old Mine Cuts do not have.

### What color grade should I choose for a square cushion cut diamond?
G or F in GIA natural is the optimal choice. The square cushion's wide face-up table displays color more visibly than compact round stones — H or lower can appear faintly warm in daylight in white gold or platinum settings. G delivers colorless-appearing results in white gold at a fraction of the D premium: a GIA 1ct D-VS1 cushion costs [$4,410](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/12473312?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) versus [$1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for G-VS1 — a 133% price increase for one color grade. For lab grown, D or E color is accessible at lab pricing with no meaningful budget trade-off.

### What is a square cushion cut engagement ring?
A square cushion cut engagement ring pairs a square cushion diamond (L/W 1.00–1.05) with a setting designed for the cushion's soft-corner geometry. Solitaire four-prong settings ([$1,000–$1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) and halo settings (from [$1,780](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?style=halo&ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) are the two most popular configurations. Complete ring builds start at [$2,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a natural 1ct G-VS1 solitaire and at [$2,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for an IGI 1.5ct lab grown solitaire.

